[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Bailey is a 66-year-old gentleman with the recent diagnosis of rectal cancer, invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma.  He was found to have a hemoglobin of 12.1 in March or April of 2010, had fecal occult blood tests times three which were negative.  Had a colonoscopy, he reports, ten days ago which showed a rectal mass.  This was biopsied and revealed invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma.  Had a CT of the abdomen and pelvis which was negative for metastatic disease.  However, it reported irregularity and thickening of the rectosigmoid wall.  Suspect neoplastic change in this region.  That was done June 16, 2010.  His symptoms at the time in March and April were one-to-two loose stools a day.  He has not noticed any melena or hematochezia.  He denies any abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, fevers, chills, night sweats, weight-loss, etc.  He is able to do his ADLs.  His colon cancer screening in the past has been fecal occult blood tests yearly since the age of 55 which have been negative.  He has been on iron replacement therapy for his low hemoglobin.

[end section id="20103"]

